### Type Assertions

Type assertions access the underlying concrete value of an interface.

### Basic Syntax

```go
var i any = "hello"

s := i.(string)       // panics if i is not string
fmt.Println(s)        // "hello"
```

### Safe Assertion

```go
var i any = "hello"

s, ok := i.(string)   // ok is true
fmt.Println(s, ok)    // "hello" true

n, ok := i.(int)      // ok is false
fmt.Println(n, ok)    // 0 false (n is zero value)
```

Without `ok`, a failed assertion panics. Always use the safe form unless you're certain.

### Assertion to Interface

```go
var i any = "hello"

// Assert to a different interface
if s, ok := i.(fmt.Stringer); ok {
    fmt.Println(s.String())
}
```

### Pattern: Type-Dependent Logic

```go
func process(v any) {
    if s, ok := v.(string); ok {
        fmt.Println("String length:", len(s))
    } else if n, ok := v.(int); ok {
        fmt.Println("Integer doubled:", n*2)
    }
}
```

### Assertion on nil Interface

```go
var i any // nil

_, ok := i.(string)  // ok is false, no panic
// s := i.(string)   // PANIC: interface conversion on nil
```

### Internal Mechanism

```go
// Syntax: x.(T)
// If T is concrete type: checks if x is T
// If T is interface type: checks if x implements T

var r io.Reader = bytes.NewReader([]byte("hello"))

// Concrete type assertion
br := r.(*bytes.Reader)  // check if r is *bytes.Reader

// Interface assertion
w := r.(io.Writer)       // check if r implements io.Writer
```

> **Key Point:** Always use the two-value form `(value, ok)` for type assertions unless you are absolutely certain the assertion will succeed. Failed assertions without `ok` cause panics.

codeExample:
package main

import "fmt"

func printValue(v any) {
    if s, ok := v.(string); ok {
        fmt.Println("String:", s)
    } else if n, ok := v.(int); ok {
        fmt.Println("Int:", n)
    } else if f, ok := v.(float64); ok {
        fmt.Println("Float:", f)
    } else {
        fmt.Println("Unknown type")
    }
}

func main() {
    printValue("hello")
    printValue(42)
    printValue(3.14)
    printValue(true)
}
